result.execSummary:
The defendant Tara L Mohr was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case. One or more other charges in this case were dismissed. The dismissed charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Tara L Mohr is presumed innocent of the dismissed charges.

  • Tara L Mohr was found guilty of Possession of Narcotic Drugs, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(am).
  • Tara L Mohr was found guilty of Possess Drug Paraphernalia, an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 961.573(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Submit to an AODA assessment, follow through with any treatment, counseling.  No use or possession of alcohol or illegal drugs/drug paraphernalia. Comply with random urine screens.  Maintain absolute sobriety. No use or possession of prescription drugs without a valid prescription. Valid prescriptions only with prior agent approval and to be taken only in the manner they are ordered.  Inform Agent of all prescriptions.

No association with any known drug users or dealers and no contact at any place where illegal drugs are purchased, used, stored, packaged or distributed.
  Follow through with any treatment and/or counseling recommended by Agent.
  Maintain full time employment and/or school combination.
  Provide DNA Sample if not yet already previously obtained.
  If probation is revoked and a prison term is not ordered, or if probation is discharged/terminated, a civil judgment shall be entered against the defendant and in favor of restitution victims and government entities for outstanding financial obligations.  Collection may include income assignment.

Defendant Tara L Mohr in court with attorney Stephen P. Rypel.  Andrea M Will appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  The Court calls the case to address the motion in limine filed by the State.  The Court rules that #7 of the motion of the limine will be excluded.   Count #2 is dismissed with prejudice. The parties address the witness list and other housekeeping issues. The parties stipulate to chain of custody.  The trial is expected to last one day.    The witnesses will be excluded during testimony. The Court will permit note taking by the jurors and will permit juror questions.  The jurors enter the courtroom at 9:05 a.m.   The Court presents introductory remarks.  Clerk swears in panel of jurors.  Court conducts voir dire.  Juror Juan M. is struck for cause.  The court calls the next potential juror.  The parties conduct voir dire. Counsels exercise 4 strikes each.  12 jurors are selected.  The balance of the jurors are return to the JAR.  The clerk swears in the potential jurors.  The court presents preliminary instructions to the jurors.   Jurors are excused and the court is in recess and will reconvene at 10:15.  The court reconvenes at 10:15 and the jurors enter the courtroom.   Both parties present opening statement. The State calls its first witness Office Matthew Curran with the City of Muskego Police Department.  The witness is sworn in. The state and defense conducts direct and cross examination of the witness.  Exhibits 1 and 4 are marked and the State moves for the exhibits to be admitted into evidence.  The Court receives exhibits 1 and 4 and exhibits are moved into evidence.  Exhibit 4 is published to the jurors. Jurors submit 2 questions.  The parties have a sidebar.  The 2 questions are marked as Court Exhibit 1 and are permitted and asked of the witness.  The witness is excused.  The State calls its next witness Lieutenant Jason Ondricka with the City of Muskego Police Department.  The witness is sworn in by the clerk.  State and defense conduct direct and cross examination of the witness. Jurors submit 2 questions.  The parties have a sidebar.  The questions are marked as Court Exhibit 2 and are permitted and asked of the witness.  The witness is excused.  The State calls its next witness David Hannon with the State Crime Lab.  The State marks exhibits #2 and and moves for admittance of exhibits.  Exhibits 2 and 3 are moved into evidence and received by the Court.  The jurors are excused at 11:57.  The parties are excused and are to return at 1:00 p.m. for continuance of the jury trial.

Case recalled at 12:59 pm outside the presence of the jury.  Defendant Tara L Mohr in court with attorney Stephen P. Rypel.  Andrea M Will appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Court reviews the jury instructions and the verdicts with the parties. Court conducts colloquy with the defendant as to whether she will testify or not.  Defendant elects to testify.  Jurors return to the courtroom at 1:07 pm.  State rests.  Tara Mohr is sworn and testifies on direct by Attorney Rypel.  Cross examination by Attorney Will.  Redirect by Attorney Rypel.  Testimony is closed.  Court reads the jury instructions to the jurors. Civilian bailiff is sworn in.  The jurors retire to the the jury room to deliberate.

Jurors reached a verdit at 2:20 p.m.   The jurors finds the Defendant guilty on Counts 1 and 3.   Atty Rypel requests the jurors be polled.   The Court polls the jurors.  The Court enters judgment on the verdicts.  Exhibit #1 is returned to the State.  The Court schedules the matter for sentencing.  Bail remains as fixed.
